title: Aust bonds weaker, with few local drivers
text:
Tue, Sep 22, 2015, 4:57 PM AEST - Australia Markets closed Aust bonds weaker, with few local drivers AAP â€“ 10 minutes ago Print 
Australian bond futures prices are slightly weaker, with few local drivers to affect the market. 
National Australia Bank fixed interest strategist Skye Masters said Australian bonds had been range-bound during the local session following comments from a US Federal Reserve official which boosted confidence in the US economy. 
"There's no real drivers today," Ms Masters said. 
"It's been a very quiet session with most of the moves happening overnight." 
Ms Masters said bonds had been unmoved by the ANZ/Roy Morgan weekly consumer confidence index which rose 8.7 per cent the week Malcolm Turnbull became prime minister, bouncing back from three weeks of falls. 
The Fed last week held off on raising its interest rate but Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta president Dennis Lockhart overnight confirmed the decision was close and expects a hike before the end of the year. 
At 1630 AEST on Tuesday, the December 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.210 (implying a yield of 2.790 per cent), down from 97.245 (2.755 per cent) on Monday. 
The December 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 98.090 (1.910 per cent), down from 98.110 (1.890 per cent). 
KEY MOVEMENTS: 
* CGS 5.5pct Jan 2018, 1.906pct, from 1.879pct on Monday 
* CGS 4.25pct April 2026, 2.825pct, from 2.790pct 
Sydney Futures Exchange prices: 
* December 2015 bill futures, 97.920, from 97.920 
* March 2016 bill futures, 98.000, unchanged 
(*Closes taken at 1630 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
